poem:
The Yearnway and the Wantwarg

Beware the yearnway through the sward,
the elders shush and hush;
for footlust wakes the Wantwarg ward,
skrik-skrak! it gnaws the brush.

I strapped my stride to stubble-steel,
click-clack, my buckles sang;
a wishwhistle and willbright reel
went thrim-thrum on the tang.

I sought the wantwalk, skinny-bent,
skit-skat, the grasses splayed;
that sidetrack, free of sign and rent,
went swish; the seedheads played.

Out lurched the Wantwarg, all dusk-dark,
huff-huff! the hedgerows flew;
it smeared the sidetrack with its mark,
whirr-whap! my courage grew.

I swung my trailblade, keen and clean;
whish-whirr! my heartbeat thud;
and spilled the Wantwarg into green;
thock-thud! it met the mud.

I strode the wantwalk, winsome-warm,
Huz-zo! the thrushes trilled;
no slab-lord sign could stem its form,
whirr-whee! the meadow thrilled.

Take heart along the yearnway sward,
they still sing hush in brush;
the Wantwarg's want lies wound and shard,
skrik-skrak no more in brush.

Roulettaroo of Monte Carlo

At dusk by Monte Carlo quay
chandeliers shiver-bright;
clink-clack the chips in flurry-play,
hush-wheels awake the night.

Beware the Roulettaroo, dear;
its luckmaws snare the bold;
Those spin-songs, crinkled, chiming clear,
ching-ching in gilded cold.

I gripped my probablade tight;
a martingrail I tied;
with riskwisp cloak and nervelight,
whirr-whirr, my heart replied.

Velvetward crept Roulettaroo,
spin-whiskers split the din;
Its prism-pupils piped ka-loo,
click-tick from win to win.

It breathed a bias-bitter breeze;
probablade went swoop;
snick-snap! I cleaved its chance-diseased,
crash-clink the luck loops droop.

Back down the marble-murmur stair
I bore its wheelish hide;
silk-suited swankers cheered the air,
pop-pop the corks outside.

Once more by Monte Carlo quay
chandeliers shimmer-bright;
clink-clack the chips in frolic-fray,
and whisper-wheels kiss night.

Ballad of the Fuserwyrm

Take heed the sprockets' soothing whirr;
For cogs conspire—tick—click.
Fuserwyrm of snaggleworks—whirr;
It snags the sheets—cold click.

Fetch up your de-jam wanderspud;
With whisper-spray and gloves;
Prime trays—papercharm, and spud;
Wear crackle-gauntlet gloves.

Ker-chunk! The Fuserwyrm gives roar;
Skritch-scrutch! the pages squeal;
With grindleglint its rollers roar;
I hear that strangled squeal.

I thrust in, near the fuser—still;
Pfft! rubber rolllets clutch;
I tug the crumpleknot—still;
Chak-chak! release the clutch.

Back through the cubefarms—happy whirr;
Huzza! triumphant click.
No more the Fuserwyrm; sweet whirr;
Take heed of cogs that click.

Thrailthrum and the Third-Rail Hum

Hark to the third-rail hummadum,
zzzt-thrum and flicker-flare;
The sidelong sleepers muttermum
of crackle, flash, and flare.

I strapped my arc-sure scinder-sword;
whirr-click, the guardboots clasp;
For out there prowls the Thrailthrum-lord,
with zingfangs, hiss, and grasp.

I donned my glimhood, volt-veil tight;
skrit-skrat the toolsack sang;
And learned the law of zap-by-night,
no leap across the clang.

From railward fog the Thrailthrum swung,
zzrrr-zzap, a sparking maw;
Its eyes were twin blue thunderlungs,
it thrummed the lawless law.

I parried with my cleaver-gleam,
ka-chack! went cable-nerve;
One sidestep, whipsnap, volt-stream seam—
I slew it, swerved with verve.

Back home along the sidetrack lane,
ring-ding, the switchlights cheer;
We feasted on warm whistlegrain,
hip-hip, hurrahful cheer.

Hush to the third-rail hummadum,
bzz-burr beyond the glare;
Where Thrailthrum-tales in dreamdrift come,
with crackle, gleam, and flare.
